name: Katie K
text: If I could give this place even more stars I would. My family came here for the week and had an amazing time! We were in the tenting area right in front of the lake.  We had an excellent view.  The sunsets here are insane! Whether relaxing at the pool or by our tent site, all 3 of us had a great time! Also, the hospitality here is great.  Everyone very friendly.  Thank you so much for the lunch on July 4th, that was a great surprise! Will definitely be coming here often. So peaceful.

resp: {'time': 1604949989257, 'text': 'Thanks for the review and kind words Nick! Happy campers are our goal everytime!  Safe travels and be sure to come back soon! 🙂'}

name: JustGoFlyVinnie
text: I can't rate this hidden gem high enough. We got the royal treatment from the owner and staff. Jenn checked us in and was excellent in letting us get our way, moving us to our desired site, and coming to check on us. I ran into a guy name Dave, who was cleaning bathrooms, and I started asking him about the campgrounds. Who would guess the owner was cleaning the bathrooms. But if you saw the bathrooms you would understand his attention to perfection and his amazing creativity. He invited us for coffee and we got a personal tour. Their plans for this campground and conference center are extraordinary and very exciting. I think it's going to have a huge draw, and so beautiful. You can see Toronto in the distance, across Lake Ontario. Enjoy the photos. I intend to post a video soon.
resp: {'time': 1603735958781, 'text': 'Thanks so much for the kind words!  We hope to see you again soon!  Safe travels!🙂'}

name: Chris Shimmin
text:
Reservation only. $25 minimum per person.

Great views of downtown and the empire. Not crowded with the reservation only.

name: Gurleen K
text:
This rooftop is absolutely beautiful! You feel like you are sitting somewhere in the Mediterranean.  It's a great date spot as well as a place to get awesome cocktails.

I came here with some girlfriends and we had a great time!! We came just to get drinks but we ended up staying for dinner because the vibe here is amazing!! This is the most beautiful rooftop and you will get the most amazing photos as well!!

When you get out of the elevator you get greeted by the most friendly staff (rare in NYC). Then they take your temperature with a super cool photo monitor (you have to see it to believe it!).  There is hand sanitizer at every table and the servers are wearing masks. We appreciate the level of high safety measures being taken!! Thank you!!

Love this place and it should definitely be on your bucket list if you are in NYC.

IG- @traveleen_gurl

name: Nick Felker
text: I went to the rooftop bar, which is inside the hotel (farthest-to-the-right elevator only). I found it to be a pretty good place to drink in the city, with a good view of Penn Station and much else of the city. The drinks were a bit expensive, in particular as I had to reserve a table ahead of time. I would probably go here again though.

name: michelle rodriguez
text: Amazing service, drinks and snacks. Great views & increible decoration. Not crowded like other rooftops in the city. Would highly recommend for a date or just to have social drinks.

name: Ashlyn Belding
text:
Cocktails were average - not too memorable. I switched to wine after trying a variety of ~5 cocktails. The waitress was obviously up selling us as soon as we got to the table - offered shots (which we got), prompted us to get better alcohol instead of house (which we did); and yet service was still extremely slow. We had to ask for water multiple times. Our food came out before drinks.

Mushroom pizza was pretty good; better than the pepperoni, tomato and pepper one (tasted like Subway).

Instagramable place; cool views; but overpriced and service sucked. Would go back if the night option presented itself but not necessarily dying to go back.

name: rennae francis
text: I saw this place on Instagram and love rooftops so I said why not?! You have to make reservations in advance and pay a deposit but it gets added to your bill. The menu isn't that intense so we stuck with the pizza but the bar will make whatever drinks you want. The staff is super friendly and honestly it feels like the Hamptons in Manhattan. Should definitely check it out. They also give you a huge bowl of spicy cashews if you order it. We didn't finish half of those cashews lol but they were good.

name: Average Socialite
text: Amazing new rooftop in NYC in Chelsea - Hamptons themed with amazing drinks, food & views! COVID measures in pleace. Make sure you make a reservation and be prepared to take a ton of pics!

name: Reginald Moye
text:
Great ambiance and amazing views of the Empire State Building. Wait Staff very friendly and I was glad I picked this venue to celebrate my birthday.
Management did work with me concerning my photographer and I am grateful. It was sort of tricky trying to have memories professionally captured for my Pre-Birthday Soiree, and trying to abide with the venue restrictions on photography!!🙏
I would suggest that would be a area they should rethink and perhaps change.🤔
The drinks were awesome and I would go there again.🍷🍷🍸🍸🎉🎊

name: Lillian Esquivel (Lilly)
text: Great local but the service...not so much! The place was not that packed and always took forever to get our drinks. We were hurried out and there was A. No one waiting for our table B. There were 3 other tables that would have been available if there was another party waiting at the hostess stand or anywhere else for that matter. We ordered another round of drinks and food and we were told we had 15 mins to finish our food and drinks!!!!!!!!

Complete pass. Arrived at the place based on an Instagram review. They must have paid for it because the place is a C at best. The only thing keeping it from a F- is that is ia a roof top.

To many amazing options close by. Go elsewhere.

We arrived around 530p on a Saturday.  The place was at less than 50% occupancy.  Yet, they insisted on placing our party of three at a two person setup. Rude.

Beyond this, they had the windows shut and did not have the ac on. The place was a sauna - break a sweat hot. We opted to leave.

Ezy, the floor manager, was rude to my party and the one in front of us.   Customer service is not his strong suit. When we left another couple left as well and the only sizable party they had left as well.

To add insult to injury the uniforms are horrendous. Very 1950s nursing home. I don't know who the are catering to.

Pass.

name: Shane Hatcher
text: I just can't explain how terrible this experience was for six nights. I didn't expect much from a Roadway Inn or of any Choice Hotel for a matter of fact. But this place takes the cake for the worst at service and the absolute nastiest room that I have ever stayed in. My military accommodations in Kuwait in Iraq were more attentive and clean. You shouldn't use this place if you have small children or a compromised immune system for the fact that you are likely to end up in the hospital. The place is filled with pubic hairs and cigarette smoke. The staff is miserable to include the highly impaired manager whom was clearly under the influence of something strong. Tony's attitude is award winning and demeaning. The personal insults and disregard of people with disabilities was just shameful to witness. Choice Hotels will be hearing from me and in particular about Tony's questioning of a Desert Storm Veterans disability. Tony the nasty receptionists whom has a personal calling to involve herself in others conversations and unwitting ability to propel insult toward customers valid complaints. I just can't explain how unbecoming this experience has been.

name: Jesse Teitsworth
text: DO NOT STAY HERE. Easily the worst "hotel" I've ever been to. Floors were dirty. Shower did not drain.  Bathroom was filthy. The toilet seat was left up when I got there. A colleague found nail clippings in her room. The beds were rock hard. I don't think the sheets were clean. Several rooms had people living in them. It's the only place to stay for about 40 miles, but in hind sight, it would have been worth the drive to avoid it. Truly terrible place.

name: Dani Madden
text:
If I could do lower I would and I think all the negatives speak for themselves as well as the constant changing hands shows horrible ownership but here is my personal experience.

I just had my daughters 5th birthday party at the pool. We talked with them face to face with a Penny in May in June she emailed me which I have. I called said wait for me to figure out whether or not we want food (only cake was allowed everything was to be bought from the kitchen which I understand) but she said "it was on the books"

Well day of the party July 9th show up no one knows anything about it. There was garbage all around the pool (pretty normal for this place) no chairs or tables, water everywhere not even close to the pool, & the kitchen was closed so we couldn't get food if we wanted. Only perk the man working the desk was helpful.

Called to complain to the company that I spent that much money on renting out the pool for a private event to have it go so bad. They sent me to the assistant manager who then told me this was my own fault. There needed to be a down payment and signed contract. I have witness with me as well as emails to prove there was no mention of either. He said she never would do that and I should of called to do it. Basically calling me a lair.

I am going to call corporate again because now I really want my $150 back after this.

text: My wife and I have been here twice now, and it's a really great bed and breakfast experience. Diana and Jennifer are great, and Diana makes the best breakfast. It's really so good. Both are very friendly and hospitable. The rooms are all different with different styles. But they're all well kept and comfortable. As a guest, you don't feel forced to socialize, but you're always invited to. The location is great for touring wineries or breweries as it's right in the middle of the "trail". It's also close to the town with all the restaurants. Really, if you have any interest in a bed and breakfast, you'll really like it here.

name: Steve Oelheim
text: Not at all what I expected. We were assigned this hotel while in the area for a hockey tournament. Surprised that we'd get a "resort and spa", but whatever. Then we looked at the pictures online, and it definitely looked a bit dated. Expectations were tempered. It vainly wasn't the fanciest place ever, but it was decent. No, the accommodations weren't the most modern. The regular rooms were a touch small, but they were clean and the balconies were nice. We had friends who got a suite, which was much roomier. The pool was EXCELLENT.. very large, and they even have a lifeguard on duty. Front desk staff wasn't the friendliest, but we talked to the manager a couple of times, and she was fantastic. Don't eat at the restaurant, the are CLEARLY not prepared for more than 2-3 tables at a time. We ate dinner and breakfast there, and service was painfully slow (though the good was pretty good). Very hockey-friendly hotel, had no problems with our kids playing knee hockey. They also gave us a complimentary party room for a team party. All in all, it was everything I'd expect from hotel at $109/night.

Holes in the walls, funky hallways and stairways, stained and dated furniture, moldy air conditioning units, old televisions with horrible picture quality, lights and wall switches that don't work, ...
I wish I could say you get what you pay for at almost $100 a night but all things considered, $60 a night would be pushing it for this place. The only saving grace in my experience, is the staff being kind but that only goes do far too.
Someone needs to come and put some attention into this place please.....

text: Absolutely horrible place. The patrons are rude and gross. The staff are no better. We went for "karaoke" night. When we asked to sing a song, the old man "dj" held up a sheet of paper with like 5 names on it and said don't bother it was gonna be a long wait. So we sat and tried to wait. The problem is that a bunch of woo hoo girls (and not the good kind) were holding on to mics, listening to their own music, and occasionally throwing in a lyric of a refrain of a song. The same 6 girls held the microphones and proceeded to have their own conversation. Not letting anyone do actual karaoke. When we reviewed on Facebook, the staff was quite snarky and retorted with "well we are sorry you didn't have fun like everyone else did" and "that is how they like to do karaoke here" umm, pardon me but 1. That isn't karaoke, and 2 you will never attract new customers with attitudes like that. You could not pay me enough to go back in there after they ruined my birthday with this sorry excuse for a bar with an advertised karaoke night.

I then sat through two more songs with the same drunk 7 women holding the microphones and occasionally singing a half chorus of whatever lame song they chose. It was a terrible experience and the locals give dirty looks to outsiders, and if made me feel like I was in the film Deliverance.  Good luck!

name: Meqren Al Mutairi
text: Saddest part about my review is that I come here VERY often. My last visit I wasn’t to satisfied with the cleanliness of my bed and sheets. Recycling sheets and pillows after a long time of being used, is completely unsanitary. A low budget hotel or not, there’s certain requirements when running an establishment like so. Also, I just currently came here and I’ve never heard of a hotel that doesn’t let you check in until 4 pm especially when check out for previous over night guests is at 12 pm. No one can wait in the lobby. I took 2 hours to get here and I’m pregnant, the receptionist explained that I couldn’t wait until check in time which was only a hour to come after my arrival. This is unacceptable and unprofessional. With the amount of funds this hotel receives everyday there is no reason that you guys still have yet to buy new things, upgrade items and at least train your workers with common courtesy. Honestly, if this problem persists... as a active member of the community board, I will gladly bring this problem to their attention and push for a thorough investigation. As I said it’s understood what type of low class establishment you guys are running but professionalism and hospitality should still be a must especially when I’m spending my money here faithfully!

name: Bridgett Donnelly
text: I was only in town for 1 night and wasn't looking to spend a whole lot. Lesson learned. When I got there the manager was at the front desk, playing on his cell phone, and didn't even bother to acknowledge my existence for a good 2-3 minutes while he finished what he was doing. No  'hello', 'how are you', nothing. I got a frank "Checking out?" "Yes, at 3:30p I am checking out." "Huh", messes around silently with the computer for another 1-2 min, "Are you Bridgett? I need your credit card". We get checked in and he tells me I'm going to need to wait while he tried to find the housekeeper because she was supposed to call him at 3 to tell him rooms were cleaned but "apparently has chosen not to today". Professional. Comes back 5 minutes later to tell me I can go to my room. The room. Wow. Carpets look like they hadn't been vacuumed in weeks. Room smelled like musty, stale cigarettes. The window curtains were stained with God knows what (probably uncleaned blood for the brutal attack that happened there 6/5/2016-as i learned later). Around midnight, there's a knock on my room door. By the time I get to the door, gone. I make sure the door is double locked from the inside and get back in bed. Then I can hear someone outside the room with a key trying to get in the room. I get up, throw the door open, and asked "what can I do for you?" This poor guy apologizes, saying he saw the door tag on the door and informed the desk clerk that someone was in this room but they insisted the room was empty and told him to try getting in anyways. Wonderful. Beds suck and are uncomfortable but at this point are the least of my concerns. The next morning I woke up to staff outside my door very loudly complaining about another customer that had just checked out. When I checked out the woman at the front told me I was all set and asked "Did someone come to your door last night? We don't even have you in our system". Really? Because the guy clearly knew my name and took my money. "Oh yeah, that was the manager. He can be a bonehead." Absolutely unreal. The entire stay was disgusting from services to conditions of the room. I'll never waste my money with Days Inn again.

text: The entire place smelt of cigarette smoke. The sheets were rough, and the bed was lumpy. Our bathroom light was out and could not be replaced (maintenance was off). name: Amy Warner
text:
Located close to the jail and airport, this Days Inn is horrible. The building reaks of cigarettes, as if the hotel only became non-smoking an hour before our arrival.

In the room nothing worked or was connected. You could only watch TV of you could figure out the proper way to hookup and program the cable box. Air conditioning was an almost laughable myth. First you have to plug it in yourself. Then it doesn't cool the air, just blows the hot air gently around the curtains. Don't bother trying to call the front desk. Your phone phone, clearly marked as being from a room on a different floor, has a dial tone, but none of the keys work. It would matter anyway, there is no maintenance staff to fix the air conditioning, out phone. While there was a mini fridge and a microwave, they had be negated for some time. Freezer burned food had become one with the tiny freezer unit in the fridge.

The bathroom was usable, but only just. For a family of four, only two bath towels, one hand towel, and one wash cloth were provided. The empty tissue box was left in the wall dispenser with no replacement available. One roll of toilet paper was provided on the back of the toilet, as the two holders were broken. Black mold is clearly visible on the drop ceiling and in every corner.

The bed was a long size as advertised. Being extra soft and springy, the toddler found it worked best as a trampoline.

Moral of the story: the Hilton, a block closer to the airport, is worth the $45 more a night.

name: Will Warner
text: Complete dive of a hotel. The entire building, including the non-smoking room my family had, reeked of old cigarette smoke, the bed had no support left in it whatsoever, the air conditioning did not work (either to cool air or even move it around!), the window did not open, and even if it could, the screen was destroyed, bathroom fixtures were rusty and some broken, grounds were unkempt and overgrown, and the location, while nice and close to the airport, is across the street from a youth correctional facility and next door to a car rental and shipping depot. This was nowhere near worth the $99/night rate for the park and fly package. I will gladly spend more for future trips to never stay at this dump ever again.

name: Daniel Ladd
text: My girlfriend and I wanted to take a romantic weekend in North Creek and the Copperfield seemed like a nice hotel given the photos and extravagant prices. We arrived at the Inn and it was sub-par, the rooms were out of date, and things were starting to fall apart. Our mirror in the bathroom was held together by duct tape and the towel rack fell off the wall when I removed a towel. We paid a lot of money for a "package deal' that came with an $80 gift card to their two "amazing" restaurants. We were excited to go to Lorenzo's which was supposed to be the higher end restaurant, but it was never open. Since Traveler's was the only other place to take the gift card we had to go there, the food was pretty good but the service was absolutely horrible. There were four waitresses standing around talking the whole night while one poor waiter tried to keep up with every table. They also forgot to tell us that neither of the restaurants are open on Sunday so we were left with $30 on the gift card that could never be used. Lucky enough we got part of that gift card money refunded but it took some work. You can find a much better quality hotel for less money.

They didn't change my room so I left. I went to Motel 6 and something must have been going on in the area because that was the only hotel available in Long Island City.  The only people there were others who couldn't find rooms at other hotels.  When I checked in,  I told the gentleman behind the desk of my experience at The Country Inn, and he laughed and said "The phone here probably won't work either ". I thought he was joking until I got to the room and there was no closet, no ironing board or iron, the phone didn't work,  amongst other things.  I went to the front desk and the guy said that he'd make a note of it and if have to talk to the manager in the morning.  The manager the next day didn't come in until noon and still didn't care and did nothing about the issue.  I'd never stay there again and would recommend others not to go.  Also it was the midst expensive Motel 6 ive ever stayed at.  Over $200 for a terrible room.

text: What a great piece of history and excellent staff! Friendly and accommodating and Family owned for 99 years! A must see if you are in the area! name: todder's channel
text: Great soup. Old school, I mean real old school sandwiches.  Where else can you get a limburger cheese sandwich? Or a liverwurst sandwich.   Did I mention absolutely delicious soup.  If you love an old building with some charm this should be on your list.  Again did I say the soup is incredible.

name: Frank Coriddi
text: Excellent homemade soup and sandwiches. The food was delicious and hot, the way it is supposed to be served, and the beer was nice and cold. I always like trying soups when I eat out. I had the yellow split soup and my wife had the garbage plate soup, both were served nice and hot and were very good. My wife also enjoyed her buffalo chicken wing wrap, as I did a turkey reuben on rye. Again, both sandwiches were served nice and hot. We have lived south of Lima for many years and wish we had tried the American Hotel sooner. We'll definitely be back.

name: Hugo Stackel
text:
I was told by a friend that this place is very good; he was absolutely right too! Our group decided to order the soups of the day- and there were a half dozen tempting offerings. I was torn between the Pork and Barley or the Cheeseburger Chowder. I ended up ordering the Cheeseburger Chowder and was very pleased with my selection. My only regret is that I ordered a cup rather than a bowl, because it was simply excellent! My companions opted for the French Onion Soup and they both raved about it. To go with our soups, we all ordered sandwiches- I had the Grilled Cheese, they had Reubens. Again, all of us agreed that our sandwiches were very tasty! I was very happy with the quality of the food, it was better than average. I feel the portions were generous too, as well as everything seemed very fresh and delicious.

Beyond the very satisfying meals, we all enjoyed the ambiance of this establishment. When you reach the front door, you immediately take note of a small plaque denoting that the place goes back to 1861, as a history buff I really found this interesting. It's clear that the building has been around a LONG time, it has the charm. It is a well maintained looking place and oozes charm and warmth. It was interesting to read that the same family has owned and operated the place for a century and it is also a functioning hotel! Pretty cool!

The service was good, our server was friendly and attentive, and the prices were reasonable and fair. So, overall, in every aspect...The American Hotel left us pleased with our decision to check it out. We left saying that we would return! This place would make most people happy in my opinion!

name: Shannon Gracie
text: Wonderful service. Great food. We will be back!

name: John Rick
text:

Beautiful, historical hotel owned by the same family for 99 years! They still do things the old fashioned way, even using the old antique cash register!
A simple menu with a choice of 5 or 6 homemade soups that continually change. You can even get a limburger cheese or liverwurst sandwich. Their gyros looked wonderful. Free cookie with your check is a nice touch!

name: Louise Orrock
text: I stayed here a week and found it to be a lovely hotel.  I first had a very nice room at the front and then moved to a suite at the back, both on the top floor, which I think was the sixth or seventh.  I then, unfortunately, renewed via the internet and opted for a slightly cheaper room on the floor below, the mouse visitor having apparently left - true and not being snide, it was very small and the rooms were very clean - I put down food for it but then it disappeared.  There was some problem with the room change and I was asked to leave, perhaps because they found out about the mice feeding, and there were no rooms available on subsequent visits.  However, it was one of the nicest hotels I've stayed in and convenient for food and I would highly recommend it, although having to be accompanied in the lift was slightly stressful and it's quite a long work otherwise.

name: Kevin Anderson
text: Not a bad little place if you need something midtown for cheap. Rooms are decent, nice tv's and the bathrooms are clean!

name: Michelle Johnson
text: The design, layout and location of the hotel are great. You can take a nice stroll to Madison Square Park or the Empire State building. I love the TV service and mini fridge and the suite setup I had. However, I can only see more negatives about this hotel than I can see positive. I want to honestly say the hotel isn't worth what I paid for. It has cheap quality for expensive prices. I was already concerned when the receptionist looked like he didn't know what he was doing every time I walked through the lobby. I was right to be concerned because they put me in the wrong room. I will applaud the fast speed of resolving that issue, however; there were only two outlets in the room, both at very awkward and inconvenient locations. At one point the outlet fried my charger, forcing me to buy a new one after the receptionist looked clueless about my complaint. The toilet doesn't flush all the way, you'll have to flush it twice to get even a small sheet of tissue down. That was a big turn off for me. They deducted an extra $25 as a deposit in case there was any damages in the room after I left, this would be returned to my card if no damages were made. I can definitely understand this, but it was not mentioned to me at all upon booking my room which was very upsetting. When I first initially reserved the room, I was informed my grand total would be $380, but then the price raised to $410, and then it raised to $477. I don't understand why because I booked the room for what it was worth at $380 but ended up paying $477, such a total ripoff. I saw reviews and was warned by a random user to book somewhere else. But knowing we as humans have different tastes, I booked it anyway to give it a chance. But I'm very bitter about my stay overall and will not suggest this place to anyone. I wish I took the advice to book somewhere else.

They helped out and found me and the family a place to crash the night before Mommy's race. Older establishment, but clean, and with very courteous staff. name: John S.
text: The 5 star rating is for the cabin my daughter and her family occupied which was fully furnished, had modern kitchen and bath and in a good location. My wife and I were in a barebones building that was due for floor and shower stall replacement. In fairness, these are old buildings that are probably updated when funds are available.  If you are a tent camper, accustomed to leaking tents and damp ground conditions our accommodation would be considered a "glamping" experience. And, for $585 for 7 nights this cabin is a bargain. Access to a beautiful lake with swimming, boating and fishing at your doorstep is a wonderful experience. Office and maintenance staff are wonderful people who respond to your needs.  Be aware that some cabins are accessed from upper road parking down pretty steep lawns.  Some renters were using their trucks and SUVs with AWD and 4WD to drive down grass slopes to unload and load their vehicles. I couldn't do this with my vehicle and had to make many trips back and forth to it arriving and departing. OK if your capable but consider cabin 155 with roadside parking if you're not.

text:
(Translated by Google) The hotel is located in NY on Butler Street in a small business park. There are car repair shops across the street. There is also work at night. So it is very loud there.
American breakfast is available.
The entire staff is extremely friendly and helpful. It is approx. 10 to 15 minutes to the NY subway station Atlantic Terminal. Various subways leave from there. Another stop is Union Street. This is a little closer, but there are fewer subways there. You can be in Manhattan in about 20 minutes.
The hotel is simple and clean. However, because of the extreme volume at night, I would not recommend it. The rooms are also noisy.
There is no safe and no refrigerator in the room.
WiFi is free of charge, as is the use of the PC in the entrance area.

Es wird amerikanisches Frühstück angeboten.
Das gesamte Personal ist überaus freundlich und hilfsbereit. Bis zur NY-Subway- Station Atlantic Terminal sind es ca. 10 bis 15 Minuten. Dort fahren verschiedene U-Bahnen ab. Eine weitere Station ist Union Street. Diese ist etwas näher, allerdings fahren dort weniger U-Bahnen. Man ist in ca. 20 Minuten in Manhatten.

name: Mr Azlan the Landlord
text:
Unhelpful reception. They are not empowered to do anything; not even pass on defect info to maintenance. They won’t even accept deliveries (courier) on behalf of guests, so I had to camp out at reception all day for UPS to arrive. The rooms are tiny, 15 ft by 15 ft at most and the ensuite toilet was an afterthought. Check in time is 1600 hrs; if you arrive early, as we did, we had to leave and come back after 1600 hrs. They charge USD7 for every piece of luggage stored in their luggage room.  A rip off, if you ask me; but we didn’t have a choice. Opportunist capitalists!

On the plus side, at USD29/night the rate is considered the cheapest in NYC; the fridge is large and they supply towels. The only useful thing reception did for us was to give us two sets of keys.

Pity we don’t have much of a choice.

name: Mark Reed
text: We recently had an appreciation banquet for our pastor. In time past, the service was deserving of a 5 star and the reason we decided to have the event there. We were told that the space-room would be ready upon our arrival at 12 as the event started at 4pm. We arrived at 1pm to a dirty banquet hall. It was not cleaned from the event the night before. We assisted with the clean up and set up of the room to ensure it was ready by 4pm. Unfortunately with all our effort, the room was not ready at 4. Dinner was set to be served at 5:30pm. Prior to dinner we discover that most of the glassware was dirty, some with lipstick. We ran out of food and had to find someone to refill it as servers was not available. We spoke with the owner afterwards. He was extremely rude and offered no resolution. We will not be returning and would not recommend this venue.

name: Zowwee Luciano
text: There were no towels or toilet paper in the room. I was handed towels only and a roll of toilet paper. No shampoo or tissues or garbage bags. The light in the bathroom flickered. The halls smelled of weed and sewage. People stood outside by where the cars parked, smoking. The pool was open but not the hot tub. The temperature fluctuated in the main areas constantly. When we went to check out, there was no one at the desk, only a note that they would be back soon with an emergency number, so we waited 10 minutes for someone to come back. The most positive thing was the cleaning staff who was very friendly.

name: Shane O'Malley
text: This place is so bad, they probably won't stay open much longer. No towels, soap or shampoo were in the rooms on arrival. Very few of the side doors worked to let you in. The bar has no drafts. Would recommend staying anywhere but here.

name: OA Dorsey
text:
This hotel is one of the worse hotels ever in Rochester, NY. I was here for an event on Saturday,  and there was absolutely no staff provided for the function, the room was not even set up, the food was HORRIBLE, and the sound system wad a total disaster.  I have worked I banqueting before and this hotel does not have what it takes to host events. The manager was very unprofessional and rude,  and so was the events coordinator....she was so rude and had no professional decorum.  She walked around the room I flip flops serving the guest the worst lemonade EVER. Then after we are, there was no one to take our plates. They stayed on the function until the event ended.....WHO DOES THAT!

This hotel has change management more times than I care to remember.  I would not consider this place to host any event ever again. The only person who is even worth mentioning is Michael (recently hired.) who was so nice and assisted us in whatever we needed(he was not even suppose to be there.) I was so disappointed at the service we received,  I would never think of coming back to this hotel for any function even a stay if I could help it.

Spider webs in the room by the lights. Parking lot full of garbage and the outside area by doors full of cigarette butts and garbage. They don’t deep clean in-between guests is the first thing that comes to mind as a reason for that. I don’t know. For a more expensive room in the area, I really expected more. name: Chris S
text: The day before I was staying at the hotel I recieved a phone call saying due to renovations there will be no continental breakfast and the pool will not be open. They took $15 off the stay. I was ok with that. Upon check in(3pm), I tried to find the entrance. The one that looked like it had tarps and dust all over. It looked like an abandoned building. I called to confirm the entrance and was told it was. There was plastic and dust everywhere in the "lobby". I brushed it off since they gave me a discount.  I got to the room and the key didn't work. The couple next door were having the same problem. Luckily the second key worked so I didn't have to go bacl to the front desk. I wanted to take a nap but it was still light out. When I went to close the curtains, I noticed they were very dirty. It was like someone with oil on there hands closed them. After my nap I wanted to watch t.v. but the satellite was down... I was quite disappointed but at least the wifi worked. The next morning when I went to shower I noticed quite a but of black mold on the ceiling and wallpaper in the shower. It made me feel dirtier than before I showered. I went to make coffee and of course remnants of the previous guests were still in the coffee maker. What a surprise. I should have taken the free cancelation and booked somewhere else...

name: Patrick Mullins
text: Too many positive vocabulary words to use regarding this hotel. Firstly, what a gorgeous neighborhood! Old New York, clear as day! Gorgeous views of the Brooklyn Bridge! Large pedestrian-friendly location with rental bikes and a pick-up location for various tours. Staff is FIVE STAR. The manager was voraciously accommodating and made sure we had everything we needed while seeming genuinely happy to be at work. And the attitude showed throughout the establishment. It was my mom's first time to New York and it couldn't have been more perfect! Thank you so much for making this an unforgettable trip!

name: Rajsri Bipat
text: This hotel is great because of the location and convenience of being in downtown Manhattan. It's an old building, with old elevators. Could use some updating. The rooms are nice enough but not nice enough for the $$ that they charge per night. Breakfast was basically a cold breakfast, except for the "eggs" which I think were badly reconstituted powdered eggs. I've stayed in hotels that cost way less, but have infinitely better breakfasts.

name: Jo Hawke
text: Although we've been to the City many times over the years, July 2015 was our first time staying at this hotel or in Seaport. Our room was clean, and most of the staff was very nice (one of the breakfast ladies got an attitude when we asked for cream cheese for the bagels...they were out). The neighborhood was nice, a lot more quiet compared to uptown where we usually stay, especially at night. The Fulton St station we needed was down, unfortunately, though, so we ended up having to walk to City Hall every time: a brisk 12-15 minutes. It was pretty inconvenient, but we got a lot of exercise. :) The parking rates listed on their website were not updated, so be sure to clarify this before you book.

name: Dale Campbell
text: Great hotel. However the room I paid for was not avaiable when I checked in and they tried to cover it up by giving me an upgrade. The room I was upgraded to was smaller than I needed for the first night. Otherwise it was an awesome experience.

name: Abraham Taub
text: This is not a 5 star hotel, but it sure is a nice and cozy place to stay in Downtown, NY. The room was clean and spacious, the clerk at the front desk was extraordinarily nice, and the staff was very helpful.

That extra effort didn't go unnoticed. Plan to visit again. Staff was nice especially since I arrived at 3 a. m. Still respectful and friendly

text: Entire hotel only has two bathtubs let's start there. My first room was a closet with a kitchenette and bathroom in it and my "terrace" was a shared courtyard with four other rooms. There is no ice machine. And the hot water is lukewarm...two days worth of lukewarm shower water yet kitchen sink stayed hot. Pots, pans, plates, and silverware were very convenient and free upon request. Jennifer the front desk girl for the mornings was awesome!

name: Ed Padin
text: Nice place. Room was small,  but clean. Cement floors are cold. Weird millenial style decor. Still, it was perfectly serviceable as a place to spend the night. The bed was comfy.

name: J. W.
text: Cute room. Front desk staff couldn't find my reservation...took us over 20 mins to check in. She said she was giving us a room with two queens or a king and a better room for the inconvenience. Got to the room and had one queen, facing busy street. Went down and asked about the beds literally 60 seconds later. She acted like she had never seen me before. Decent hotel, decent location.

name: Marcos Farion Jr.
text: Must be nice in good weather. When it's cold you don't use the outside facilities. Our room supposed to be in upper levels but they got as the ground level. They forgot the housekeeping one day even tho we asked personally (they did it correctly the other days). Everyday is a new person in the front desk, I didn't like that, felt like in a hostel not a hotel. Rooms were clean when we got there, plenty of space to live, cook, etc. Out air conditioner was on the floor, beside the bed, so you can't sleep with the hot air straight to your face. There was no heater in our room (which is weird because the corridor had) just the air conditioner and a small portable heater. The WC is nice but the water does not get hot enough. When it's 30F outside it does make a big difference. TV is nice, a big 55" brand new and good channels. Goos location, at least 4 dofferent metro lines go there as I can remember now. The line 1 RED stops right in front of it. We recommend, but be aware of all above.

name: Douglas Fernandez
text: It was a cool trendy spot. Loads of board games. Had a Shabby Chic aesthetic. Bed wasn't very comfortable. And the only give one towel per person. Felt more like an apartment then a hotel room.

name: DD O
text: Terrific alternative to old downtown brand names. Great loft fun too!

name: Chloe Fuchs
text:
The customer service was alright but new management is clearly needed. The entrance is super sketchy and unless you're from NYC you'd think it was illegitimate. The room took way too long to be cleaned, there was still hair in the shower catch and our toilet was clogged when we got there. When we asked for someone to come up and help, the front door girl showed up with a plunger and meekly handed it to us to do ourselves.

On top of that, who ever hired the contractors to develop this hotel should be sued and then lose their licenses, there was dried grout all over the tiles, holes and pencil markings all over the walls, there are light switches that don't turn anything on and lights that have no switch! Our phone wasn't working so the handy man had to come in and out several times; turns out it wasn't even plugged in. The walls are incredible thin, we could hear someone else's TV blaring from down the hall and the gap between the door and floor is so huge you can see the feet of those who walk by.

The positives, very close to the subway and has a market right next door. The room are a nice space and while there clearly needs to be a management overhaul, it's clear that the front desk staff and handymen have good intentions and were very polite.
